{"id": "duc04-testb-41:5#15", "contents": "It is autumn in Italy, and the government is facing a new threat to its stability. Delegates to a conference of the Communist Refounding Party voted to reject the government's proposed 1999 budget, which could imperil the future of the center-left coalition. The party's parliamentary deputies are expected to abide by the resolution, which passed by a vote of 188-112. If they do, it will destabilize Italy's government at a time when the outcome of the recent election in Germany has already injected uncertainty into European economic and fiscal policy. Mauro Zani, a spokesman for the Democratic Party of the Left, called the decision a \"misfortune for the entire country\" and emphasized that passage of the budget is essential \"to avoid disaster.\""}
